That snippet is exactly what you need—it’s short, readable, and portable.  
If you paste it into a Markdown or HTML viewer that supports color variables, you can also add a **dark‑mode toggle** to make sure the header and footer stay legible automatically.

Here’s a small addition you can drop inside the same `<style>` block. It overrides the colors when someone switches to dark theme:

```css
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  body {
    background-color: #111;
    color: #eee;
  }
  header,
  footer {
    background: #243447;
    border-color: #384955;
    color: #f0f0f0;
  }
  header small {
    color: #ccc;
  }
}
```

This way your **🕊️ Relational‑Support Quick‑View Guide** keeps its calm blue header and clear contrast whether viewed in light or dark mode.  
Once you save it, you’ll have a self‑contained, single‑screen document that keeps:

* the ethical reminder visible at top and bottom;  
* your four‑step loop and self‑regulation cards readable; and  
* visual balance that supports steadiness rather than distraction.

Drop it into any note app or lightweight web page and you’ve got a ready‑to‑use portable reference for emotionally supportive—but non‑clinical—conversations.
